# Rabies After a Dog Bite: Everything You Need to Know About PEP, Vaccines, and the NCDC Schedule

**By RxMedCalc | Reviewed by an MBBS, AFIH Certified Physician | Based on NCDC India & WHO Guidelines**

---

A dog bite. A scratch from a stray cat. A monkey snatching food and grazing your hand. These moments happen every day across India — and in the panic that follows, most people don't know what to do next, or how serious the risk actually is.

Rabies is one of the most feared diseases in medicine, and for good reason: **once symptoms appear, it is almost always fatal.** There are fewer than a handful of documented human survivors in recorded medical history.

And yet — rabies is also **100% preventable** if you act quickly and correctly after an exposure.

This guide covers everything you need to know: what rabies is, how it spreads, how to classify your exposure, what post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) involves, and exactly what the Indian NCDC-recommended vaccination schedule looks like — in plain language, for both patients and clinicians.

---

## What Is Rabies?

Rabies is a viral disease caused by the **Rabies lyssavirus**, which attacks the central nervous system. Once the virus reaches the brain, it causes progressive and fatal encephalitis (brain inflammation).

The virus is almost always transmitted through the **saliva of an infected animal** — typically via a bite, but also through scratches or licks on broken skin or mucous membranes.

In India, **dogs are responsible for over 96% of rabies deaths** in humans. Other animals that can transmit rabies include cats, monkeys, jackals, foxes, and bats.

India accounts for approximately **36% of the world's rabies deaths** — around 18,000–20,000 people per year. Most of these deaths are preventable with timely post-exposure prophylaxis.

---

## How Rabies Spreads — And How It Doesn't

**Rabies CAN spread through:**
- Bite wounds from an infected animal (most common)
- Scratches that break the skin
- Licks on open wounds, cuts, or mucous membranes (eyes, mouth, nose)
- Rarely, organ transplants from infected donors

**Rabies CANNOT spread through:**
- Intact, unbroken skin
- Touching or petting an infected animal
- Blood, urine, or faeces of an infected animal
- Contact with a vaccinated domestic pet that has no symptoms

---

## Recognising Rabies in an Animal

Not every animal bite comes from a rabid animal — but you cannot know for certain at the time of exposure. These are warning signs in animals:

- Unprovoked aggression or biting
- Excessive drooling or foaming at the mouth
- Disorientation, staggering, appearing "drunk"
- Hydrophobia (fear of water) — visible as difficulty swallowing
- Paralysis of the jaw or hind legs
- A normally nocturnal animal (like a bat) appearing in daylight

**Important:** A healthy-looking animal can still be in the early stages of rabies. Do not wait to see if the animal develops symptoms before seeking medical care. Observe the animal only in addition to seeking treatment — never instead of it.

---

## Exposure Categories: I, II, and III

The first thing a doctor will assess after an animal exposure is the **category of exposure**, as defined by the WHO and NCDC India. This determines what treatment you need.

### Category I — No Exposure
- Touching or feeding animals
- Licks on intact (unbroken) skin
- **No PEP required** — wash hands thoroughly

### Category II — Minor Exposure
- Nibbling of uncovered skin
- Minor scratches or abrasions **without bleeding**
- **PEP required:** Anti-Rabies Vaccine (ARV) only

### Category III — Severe Exposure
- Single or multiple transdermal bites (skin broken)
- Scratches that cause bleeding
- Contamination of mucous membranes (eyes, mouth, nose) with saliva
- Licks on broken skin
- Exposure to bats
- **PEP required:** ARV **plus** Rabies Immunoglobulin (RIG) on Day 0

When in doubt, treat the exposure as Category III. It is always safer to do more.

---

## What to Do in the First 15 Minutes — First Aid at Home

Before you even reach a hospital, the single most important thing you can do is **wash the wound immediately**.

### The Correct First Aid Protocol:

1. **Wash with soap and running water for at least 15 minutes.** This is not optional — thorough washing alone significantly reduces the chance of the virus entering nerve tissue. Use any soap available.

2. **Apply an antiseptic.** Povidone-iodine (Betadine), 70% ethanol, or any iodine-based solution should be applied after washing.

3. **Do not suture the wound immediately.** If suturing is necessary, delay it by a few hours after RIG has been infiltrated into the wound (in Category III cases). This allows RIG to neutralise any virus present before it is sealed in.

4. **Do not apply chilli powder, oil, turmeric, or any home remedies.** These are harmful and delay proper treatment.

5. **Go to a hospital immediately.** Do not wait until the next day.

---

## Post-Exposure Prophylaxis (PEP) — The Treatment That Saves Lives

Post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) is the medical term for the treatment given after a rabies exposure to prevent the disease from developing. It has two components:

### 1. Anti-Rabies Vaccine (ARV)

The ARV is a killed (inactivated) virus vaccine given as an injection. It works by stimulating your immune system to produce antibodies against the rabies virus.

In India, the NCDC recommends the **4-dose Essen Intramuscular (IM) regimen:**

| Dose | Day | Notes |
|------|-----|-------|
| Dose 1 | Day 0 | Same day as bite — as early as possible |
| Dose 2 | Day 3 | 3 days after Dose 1 |
| Dose 3 | Day 7 | 7 days after Dose 1 |
| Dose 4 | Day 28 | 28 days after Dose 1 |

**Day 0 means the day you receive your first injection** — not necessarily the exact day of the bite (though you should start as soon as possible).

> 💉 Use the [RxMedCalc Rabies PEP Scheduler](https://rxmedcalc.com/rabies-scheduler/) to instantly calculate your exact ARV dose dates by entering the date of your first injection.

The vaccine is given as an intramuscular injection into the **deltoid muscle** (upper arm) in adults, or the **anterolateral thigh** in young children. Never in the gluteal region (buttocks), as absorption is poor.

### 2. Rabies Immunoglobulin (RIG) — For Category III Only

RIG provides **immediate, passive immunity** — ready-made antibodies that neutralise the virus at the wound site while the vaccine takes several days to stimulate the body's own immune response. This bridging period is critical.

**RIG is given only once — on Day 0, alongside the first ARV dose.** It should never be given on a different day.

There are two types of RIG available in India:
- **ERIG (Equine RIG):** Derived from horse serum. Dose: **40 IU/kg body weight.** More widely available and less expensive. A skin sensitivity test is recommended before administration.
- **HRIG (Human RIG):** Derived from human donors. Dose: **20 IU/kg body weight.** Preferred where available due to lower risk of adverse reaction.

As much of the RIG dose as anatomically possible should be **infiltrated directly into and around the bite wound**. Any remaining volume is given as an intramuscular injection at a site distant from the vaccine injection.

> ⚖️ Use the [RxMedCalc ARV Dose & RIG Calculator](https://rxmedcalc.com/medical-calculators/arv-dose-calculator) to calculate the exact RIG dose in mL by body weight for both ERIG and HRIG.

---

## Intradermal vs. Intramuscular Route — What's the Difference?

Some government hospitals and WHO-certified centres use an **Intradermal (ID) regimen** instead of the standard IM Essen schedule. Here is a quick comparison:

| Feature | Intramuscular (IM) Essen | Intradermal (ID) |
|---------|--------------------------|------------------|
| Doses | 4 doses | 3 visits (Days 0, 3, 7) |
| Injection sites | 1 site per visit | 2 sites per visit (0.1 mL each) |
| Vaccine volume used | Full vial per dose | Fraction of vial — more economical |
| Schedule | Days 0, 3, 7, 28 | Days 0, 3, 7 |
| Availability | Most hospitals | Certified centres only |

The ID regimen is equally effective when administered correctly, but requires trained personnel and is not suitable for immunocompromised patients.

---

## What About Pre-Exposure Prophylaxis (PrEP)?

Pre-exposure prophylaxis is vaccination **before** any animal exposure occurs. It is recommended for:
- Veterinarians and animal handlers
- Laboratory workers handling rabies virus
- Wildlife workers
- Travellers spending extended time in high-risk areas

PrEP does not eliminate the need for PEP after exposure, but it simplifies the post-exposure regimen (only 2 booster doses needed, no RIG required) and provides a safety margin if treatment is delayed.

---

## Special Situations

### Immunocompromised Patients
Patients on immunosuppressive therapy, HIV-positive individuals with low CD4 counts, or those on systemic corticosteroids may have a blunted vaccine response. They may require:
- A 5th dose on Day 90
- Rabies antibody titre testing to confirm adequate response
- RIG even for Category II exposures in some cases

Always consult an infectious disease specialist for these patients.

### Previously Vaccinated Individuals
If a person has previously completed a full pre-exposure or post-exposure rabies vaccine course and has documented immunity, they require only **2 booster doses** (Days 0 and 3) — no RIG is needed.

### Pregnancy
Rabies PEP is **not contraindicated in pregnancy.** The risk of rabies is far greater than any theoretical risk from the vaccine. Pregnant women should receive the full PEP regimen including RIG where indicated.

### Children
The same dose and schedule applies to children as adults for the ARV. RIG dose is calculated by body weight (same formula). The injection site in young children is the anterolateral thigh rather than the deltoid.

---

## What Happens If You Don't Get Vaccinated?

Once the rabies virus reaches the brain, it triggers a devastating encephalitis. The incubation period — the time from bite to symptoms — typically ranges from **1 to 3 months**, but can be as short as a week or as long as a year, depending on the location and severity of the bite (bites on the face or neck progress faster due to proximity to the brain).

**Early symptoms of rabies:**
- Fever, headache, weakness
- Pain, tingling, or burning at the wound site (a characteristic early sign)
- Anxiety and agitation

**Later symptoms (encephalitic phase):**
- Hydrophobia (fear/spasm triggered by water or swallowing)
- Aerophobia (fear of air or drafts)
- Hypersalivation (excessive drooling)
- Hallucinations
- Paralysis

**Outcome:** Without prior vaccination, rabies is **essentially 100% fatal** once symptoms begin. There is no effective treatment at this stage. This is why immediate PEP is so critical — treatment must begin before the virus reaches the brain.

---

## Common Myths About Rabies in India

### "I'll wait and see if the dog dies."
**Wrong.** The dog may die — or may recover without being rabid. Either way, you lose critical time. Begin PEP immediately and monitor the animal in parallel.

### "The bite didn't bleed much, so I don't need a vaccine."
**Wrong.** Even minor scratches breaking the skin (Category II) require ARV. Category does not depend on the amount of bleeding.

### "I got vaccinated as a child, I'm protected."
**Wrong.** Childhood rabies vaccination (if given at all) does not provide lifelong immunity. A full post-exposure regimen is still required after exposure, though it may be simplified.

### "The animal was vaccinated so I'm safe."
**Possibly wrong.** Domestic pet vaccination significantly reduces risk, but you cannot verify the quality or timing of the animal's vaccination. Still seek medical evaluation for any Category II or III exposure.

### "Rabies vaccines have dangerous side effects."
**Wrong.** Modern cell-culture rabies vaccines (used in India today) are very well tolerated. Serious adverse events are rare. The old nerve tissue vaccines (NTV) with significant side effects are no longer used in India.

---

## Key Takeaways

- **Wash the wound immediately** with soap and running water for at least 15 minutes — this is your most important first action
- **All Category II and III exposures require ARV** — do not delay
- **Category III exposures also require RIG on Day 0** — it cannot be given later
- **Complete all 4 doses of ARV** — missing doses reduces protection
- **Rabies is fatal once symptomatic — but 100% preventable with timely PEP**
